Using the PShell Command to run PWSH Commands
2
The
PShell
command of TCC provides the ability to run PowerShell 5.1 commands and scripts, but it does not provide the ability to run PowerShell 7.5.4 commands and scripts.
I've started working on a method that will allow me to use the PShell Command to run PWSH Commands.
From TCC;
dos
start pwsh.exe
Paste the following into pwsh.exe, then press the enter key;
powershell
$listener = [System.Net.Sockets.TcpListener]::new([System.Net.IPAddress]::Loopback, 5555)
$listener.Start()
"Listening on 127.0.0.1:5555"
while ($true) {
    $client = $listener.AcceptTcpClient()
    $ns = $client.GetStream()
    $sr = New-Object System.IO.StreamReader($ns)
    $sw = New-Object System.IO.StreamWriter($ns)
    $sw.AutoFlush = $true
    try {
        $cmd = $sr.ReadLine()
        if ($null -eq $cmd) { $client.Close(); continue }
        if ($cmd -eq 'exit') { $sw.WriteLine(( @{ Result = 'bye' } | ConvertTo-Json -Compress )); $client.Close(); break }
        $ErrorActionPreference = 'Stop'
        $WarningPreference = 'SilentlyContinue'
        $VerbosePreference = 'SilentlyContinue'
        $InformationPreference = 'SilentlyContinue'
        $ProgressPreference = 'SilentlyContinue'
        # Execute the command and capture objects
        $result = Invoke-Expression $cmd
        # For simple, reliable transport, convert to JSON.
        # If $result is empty, send an empty array.
        if ($null -eq $result) { $payload = @() } else { $payload = $result }
        $json = $payload | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 10 -Compress
        $sw.WriteLine($json)
    } catch {
        $err = @{ Error = $_.ToString() } | ConvertTo-Json -Compress
        $sw.WriteLine($err)
    } finally {
        $client.Close()
    }
}
$listener.Stop()
Your pwsh.exe session should look similar to this;
Copy the following to a file, for example, test.ps1
# PowerShell 5.1: connect, send Get-Date, receive JSON, convert back to objects
$tcp = New-Object System.Net.Sockets.TcpClient('127.0.0.1', 5555)
$ns = $tcp.GetStream()
$sr = New-Object System.IO.StreamReader($ns)
$sw = New-Object System.IO.StreamWriter($ns)
$sw.AutoFlush = $true

# Send the command to run inside the running pwsh process
$sw.WriteLine('$PSVersionTable.PSVersion')
# $sw.WriteLine('exit')

# Read one-line JSON response
$json = $sr.ReadLine()
$tcp.Close()

# Convert JSON back to PS objects
# If the server returned an array of objects, ConvertFrom-Json yields arrays/objects
$result = $json.Trim() | ConvertFrom-Json

# The server will typically return a string or object; show it
$result
and then from TCC,
dos
pshell test.ps1
This is what is returned to my TCC session;
To end the communication between TCC and PWSH.EXE, change the following lines in test.ps1;
powershell
# Send the command to run inside the running pwsh process
# $sw.WriteLine('$PSVersionTable.PSVersion')
$sw.WriteLine('exit')
From TCC, run;
dos
pshell test.ps1
The pwsh.exe session should now be back at the prompt;
The TCC session should look like this;
I hope to streamline the process in the coming days, but for now, this is just a proof-of-concept, that it can be done.
